<subsection xml:id="subsec-zero-indices" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Zero indices</title>
        <p>
            For any natural number <m>a</m>, if it is raised to the power of zero, the result is always <m>1</m>. 
        </p>
        <p>
            This means that <m>a^0 = 1</m> for any <m>a \neq 0</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>\frac{a}{a} = 1</m>, but from indices, <m>\frac{a}{a} = a^0</m> , <m>a^0 = 1</m> for any natural number <m>a</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            Example:
        </p>
        <p>
            Lets take <m>a</m> to be <m>4</m>:
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>4^2 \div 4^2 = \frac{4^2}{4^2} = 1</m>
        </p>
        <p>
        But using the laws of indices: 
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>4^2 \div 4^2 = 4^{2-2} = 4^0</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            So: <m>4^0 = 1</m>
        </p>
        <p>
        Suppose we have <m>\frac{5^3}{5^3}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>\frac{5^3}{5^3} = 1</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            But using the laws of indices: 
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>\frac{5^3}{5^3} = 5^{3-3} = 5^0</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            Thus: <m>5^0 = 1</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            Also, if we have <m>\frac{8}{8}</m> the result is <m>1</m>. 
            This can be done using powers of numbers:
        </p>
        <p>
            That is, <m>\frac{8}{8} = 2^3 \div 2^3 = 2^{3-3}= 2^0 = 1</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            Therefore, any natural number raised to the power of zero is equal to <m>1</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            We can also use pattern recognition to verify that <m>a^0 = 1</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            Example: Powers of <m>2</m>:
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>2^3=8</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>2^2=4</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>2^1=2</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>2^0=1</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            Each step divides by <m>2</m>:
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>8 \div 2=4, 4 \div 2= 2 , 2 \div2=1</m>
        </p>
        <p>
        Thus <m>2^0 = 1</m>
        </p>
            <activity>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        
                    </p>
                    <p>
                       1. Working in groups, choose any <m>3</m> natural numbers from the list below:
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <m>2, 5, 7, 10, 25, 100</m>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        2. For each number:
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <ol marker="i)">
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Write two equal powers of the number.e.g <m> 2^3 \div 2^3</m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Simplify the expression to show that it equals <m>1</m>.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        3. Look at the pattern below and complete the missing values:
                    </p>
                <p>
                    <me>
                        2^4 = 16
                    </me>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <me>
                        2^3 = 8
                    </me>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <me>
                        2^2 = 4
                    </me>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <me>
                        2^1 = 2
                    </me>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <me>
                        2^0 = ?
                    </me>
                </p>
                <p>
                    What happens when the exponent reaches zero?
                </p>
                <p>
                    4. Discuss your work with the class.
                </p>
                </statement>
            </activity>
            <example>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                      Simplify <m>7^2 \times 7^0</m>  
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                      By definition, <m>7^0 = 1</m>.  
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Therefore, <m>7^2 \times 7^0 = 7^2 \times 1 = 7^2</m>.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Calculating <m>7^2</m> gives us:
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <m>7 \times 7 = 49</m>.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        So, <m>7^2 \times 7^0 = 49 \times 1</m>.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Hence, <m>7^2 \times 7^0 = 49</m>.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </example>

    
</subsection>